{"title_page": "Wolf Kahn", "text_new": "{{short description|German-born American painter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Wolf Kahn\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Hans Wolfgang Kahn\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1927|10|4}} \n| birth_place  = [[Stuttgart, Germany]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|3|15|1927|10|4}}\n| death_place  = \n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Painting]] and [[Pastels]]\n| training      = [[Hans Hofmann]] <br> [[University of Chicago]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n|website = {{url|wolfkahn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Wolf Kahn''' (October 4, 1927 \u2013 March 15, 2020)<ref name=\"Death\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.reformer.com/stories/southern-vermont-artist-wolf-kahn-dies-at-age-92,600135 |title=Southern Vermont artist Wolf Kahn dies at age 92 |last=LeConey |first=Bill |last2=Reformer |first2=Brattleboro |date=March 16, 2020 |website=The Brattleboro Reformer |language=en |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]]-born [[United States|American]] [[Painting|painter]].\n\nKahn, known for his combination of [[Realism (arts)|Realism]] and [[Color Field]], worked in [[pastel]] and [[oil paint]]. He studied under [[Hans Hofmann]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and also graduated from the [[University of Chicago]].{{cn|date=March 2018}} Kahn was a resident of both New York City and, during the summer and autumn, [[West Brattleboro, Vermont]].\n\n==Life and career==\nWolf Kahn was born in 1927 in [[Stuttgart, Germany]], the fourth child of Emil and Nellie Budge Kahn. Kahn's father was a notable figure in the music world. He was a musician, composer, conductor, and teacher. Kahn's family was [[Jewish]].<ref>http://www.wolfkahn.com/writing/unlocking-the-unconscious</ref> In 1933, Kahn's father lost his appointment with the Stuttgart Philharmonic Orchestra when [[Adolf Hitler]] came into power and, with increasing [[antisemitism]] sweeping Germany, he and his second wife left Germany with Kahn's three siblings for the United States. Wolf was sent to live with his grandmother, Anna Kahn, in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt, Germany]], at the age of three. He stated that he began drawing at the age of four.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.percontra.net/archive/14kahn.htm|title=Wolf Kahn, The Per Contra Interview with Miriam N. Kotzin|website=www.percontra.net|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n\nIn 1937, the summer of his 11th birthday, his grandmother signed him up for private art lessons with Miss von Joeden. He drew every day and was inspired by military pageantry, [[Napoleonic Wars]] and prominent historical figures including [[Adolph Menzel]] and [[Frederick the Great]]. In 1939, when Kahn was 12 years old, his grandmother arranged for him to leave Germany for England to live with a host family, first with the John Wade family and then with the Purvis Family. As quotas for immigrant applications in the United States changed, Kahn was able to reunite with his family in [[New York City]] in 1940 at the age of 13. {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 1942, Kahn was accepted for his sophomore year at the [[The High School of Music and Art|High School of Music and Art]] in [[New York City]].  His drawings morphed into caricatures.  Kahn cited David Low and Thomas Nast as his favorite cartoonists.<ref>Interview with Wolf Kahn and Justin Spring, July 1995</ref>  His first job was graphics editor of the school newspaper, ''The Overtone''. He graduated in 1945. After a year in the [[U.S. Navy]] after high school, Kahn first attended the [[New School]] to study painting under [[Stuart Davis (painter)|Stuart Davis]].  With the aid of the [[GI Bill]], he was able to continue his studies with [[Abstract Expressionist]] [[Hans Hofmann]] at the Hans Hofmann School.<ref name=\":1\" />  He became Hofmann\u2019s studio assistant by the summer of 1947 at Hofmann's [[Provincetown]], [[Massachusetts]] studio. In 1949, Kahn was accepted into the [[University of Chicago]]'s Hutchins Program, where he completed a bachelor's degree in eight months. {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 1956, he met fellow painter [[Emily Mason]], who he later joined in [[Venice]], Italy. They married there in March 1957 at the municipal building near the [[Rialto Bridge]], witnessed by strangers and friends including filmmaker [[Tinto Brass]]. In 1958 the couple returned to New York City where Mason gave birth to their first daughter Cecily in 1959. In 1963 the family returned to Italy. Their daughter Melany was born in [[Rome]] in 1964. In 1968 the couple bought a farm in [[Brattleboro, Vermont]] where they continued to summer. Kahn died on March 15, 2020 at the age of 92.<ref name=\"Death\" />\n\n==Wolf Kahn's art==\nKahn worked in oil and pastel.  His works usually cover the subject of [[Landscape art|landscapes]] and his own personal vision of nature.  His convergence of light and color has been described as combining \"pictorial landscapes and painterly abstraction\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/hanshofmann/wolf_kahn_001.html|title=Hans Hofmann . Hofmann\u2019s Legacy . Wolf Kahn \u2013 PBS|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref>\n\n===Influences===\nSurrounded from birth by the work of such artists as [[Hans Thoma]], [[Carl Spitzweg]], [[Wilhelm Trubner]], [[Franz Winterhalter]], by [[Edwardian]]  furniture, books and bronzes of [[Schiller]] and [[Goethe]], it is no wonder that Kahn started drawing at a very young age.  While at the University of Chicago, he became interested in philosophy, particularly the writings of [[Immanuel Kant]] while making sketches of sailboats riding anchor on [[Lake Michigan]].\n\nKahn loved the visual effects of [[Maine]]'s coastline. In the late 1960s after a number of vacations on [[Deer Isle]], Maine, the foggy conditions ultimately led to a significant shift in Kahn's painting.  Years of monochromatic work concentrated on varying tonalities finally gave way to intense color. Kahn recalled later, \"I began to let the color come through on my canvases...my pastels were always intense, and finally my painting caught up with them.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spring|first1=Justin|title=Wolf Kahn|date=2011|publisher=Abrams|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-9790-5|pages=59|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n===Exhibitions===\nKahn's very first exhibition was a group show titled, ''New Provincetown '47'', curated by [[Clement Greenberg]] at the Seligmann Gallery on 57th Street in New York.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spring|first1=|title=Wolf Kahn|date=2011|publisher=|location=|isbn=|pages=21|edition=}}</ref>  The next exhibition would be self-organized by Kahn titled ''813 Broadway'' in 1951.  This was followed by a group exhibition in the fall of 1952 at the Hansa Gallery Cooperative, one of a few Hofmann student spinoffs.  His first one-man solo exhibition would follow in 1953, also at Hansa Gallery, after a summer trip to [[Louisiana]] where he visited his art professor brother, Peter.  A real break came after living and painting in [[Tepoztlan]], Mexico, in a studio space afforded by Mrs. Norman.  Kahn returned to New York City with an offer to join Grace Borgenicht Gallery in 1955.  Her gallery had been in existence on 57th Street since May 1951.  In 1960, Kahn accepted a position as a visiting professor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].  Around this same time, his work was included in a major exhibition at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] titled ''Young America 1960: 30 Painters under 36''. Until his death, Kahn remained very active, still creating new work and exhibiting multiple times per year. <ref>[https://www.artsy.net/artist/wolf-kahn/shows List of past and current exhibitions on Artsy.net]</ref> In Winter of 2017, Kahn celebrated his 90th birthday with an exhibition of over fifty recent paintings at Miles McEnery Gallery (formerly Ameringer | McEnery | Yohe). <ref>[https://hamptonsarthub.com/2017/11/14/exhibitions-nyc-gallery-scene-highlights-through-november-19-2017/ Review of Exhibition ''Hamptons Art Hub'' November 14, 2017]</ref> <ref>[https://www.newcriterion.com/blogs/dispatch/the-critics-notebook-9193 Review of Exhibition, ''Criterion's Critic Notebook'' December 18, 2017]</ref> <ref>[http://www.artnews.com/2018/01/26/new-yorks-ameringer-mcenery-yohe-gallery-renames-expands/ ''New York's Ameringer McEnery Yohe Gallery Renames Itself, Expands'' by Alex Greenberger, Artnews.com, January 26, 2018]</ref> He was represented by several galleries, including [[Addison/Ripley Fine Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://addisonripleyfineart.com/artist/wolf-kahn-pastel/|title=.wolf kahn \u2013 pastel|website=Addison Ripley|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and memberships===\nKahn received a number of awards including a [[Fulbright Scholarship]] in 1962, a John Simon [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] in 1966, and an Award in Art from the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite journal | title= Portrait of the Artist's Market | author= Annette Grant | publisher=ARTINFO | date= February 9, 2008 | url= http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/26657/portrait-of-the-artists-market/ | accessdate=2008-04-23 | postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref> Kahn received Lifetime Achievement Awards from the Vermont Council on the Arts 1998 and the National Academy in 2006.  He received the University of Chicago Outstanding Alumni Professional Achievement Award in 2012 and the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] awarded him the International Medal of Art in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/international-medal-of-arts-winner-turns-90-wolf-kahn-shows-his-true-colors,511100|title=International Medal of Arts winner turns 90: Wolf Kahn shows his true colors|last=O'Connor|first=Kevin|date=2017-06-20|work=The Berkshire Eagle|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en}}</ref>  He has honorary doctorates from [[Wheaton College (Massachusetts)|Wheaton College]], 2000<ref>[http://wheatoncollege.edu/college-history/2000s/wolf-kahn/ \"Wolf Kahn, Honorary Degree Recipient\"], Wheaton College History.</ref> and [[Union College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://muse.union.edu/newsarchives/2004/07/page/5/|title=Archives {{!}} Union College News Archives|website=muse.union.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\nKahn became a member of the [[National Academy of Design]] in 1980 and the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] in 1984. He was on the Board of Trustees for [[Marlboro College]], in Marlboro, Vermont, and was an honorary trustee at the Brattleboro Museum in Brattleboro, Vermont.\n\nIn 2005 the Smithsonian Art Collectors Program commissioned Kahn to produce a print to benefit the cultural and educational programs of the [[Smithsonian Associates]].  The screenprint, entitled ''Aura'', hangs in the Graphic Eloquence exhibit in the [[S. Dillon Ripley Center]] on the [[National Mall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artslant.com/ew/artists/show/19487-wolf-kahn|title=Wolf Kahn|website=ArtSlant|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Museum collections===\nKahn's work can be found in numerous museum collections including:\n* [[Art Institute of Chicago]], Chicago, IL<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/73345?search_no=1&index=0|title=Barn in Blue Haze {{!}} The Art Institute of Chicago|website=www.artic.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Boca Raton Museum of Art]], Boca Raton, FL\n* [[Brooklyn Museum]], Brooklyn, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/search?keyword=wolf+kahn|title=Brooklyn Museum|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hirshhorn.si.edu/search-results/search-result-details/?edan_search_value=hmsg_87.5|title=Search Result Details \u2013 Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden {{!}} Smithsonian|work=Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden {{!}} Smithsonian|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* Colby College Museum of Art<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.colby.edu/museum/?s=wolf%20kahn&obj=CUS.18.zoomosd.6054?sid=801&x=9487&x=9488|title=wolf kahn {{!}} Search Results  {{!}} Colby College Museum of Art|work=Colby College Museum of Art|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], Los Angeles, CA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/248818|title=In Providence, R.I. {{!}} LACMA Collections|website=collections.lacma.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Memorial Art Gallery]], University of Rochester, Rochester, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://magart.rochester.edu/4DACTION/HANDLECGI/CTN1?theKW=Wolf+Kahn&RefineSearch=NewSelection|title=Memorial Art Gallery Collection-Bright Winter Day, 85.61|website=magart.rochester.edu|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search#!?q=wolf%20kahn&perPage=20&sortBy=Relevance&sortOrder=asc&offset=0&pageSize=0|title=Collection|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], Boston, MA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.org/collections/search|title=Collections Search|website=Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy Museum]], New York, NY \n* [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]], Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanart.si.edu/artist/wolf-kahn-2528|title=Wolf Kahn|website=Smithsonian American Art Museum|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* [[National Gallery of Art]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nga.gov/global-site-search-page.html?searchterm=wolf%2520kahn&searchpath=%252Fcontent%252Fngaweb%252FCollection&pageNumber=1|title=Global Site Search Page|website=www.nga.gov|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* Whitney Museum of American Art, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whitney.org/Collection/AllArtists?name=K|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410063840/http://whitney.org/Collection/AllArtists?name=K|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-04-10|title=All Artists {{!}} Whitney Museum of American Art|date=2016-04-10|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Yale University Art Gallery]], New Haven, CT<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artgallery.yale.edu/collection/search/wolf%20kahn|title=Overview and Highlights|website=artgallery.yale.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* Ackland Art Museum, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, NC\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Marika Herskovic, [http://www.worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/50666793&tab=holdings ''New York School Abstract Expressionists Artists Choice by Artists''] (New York School Press, 2000). {{ISBN|0-9677994-0-6}}, pp.&nbsp;32; 37; 194\u2013197\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/kahn_wolf.html Wolf Kahn on ARTCYCLOPEDIA]\n* [http://www.askart.com/AskART/artists/search/Search_Repeat.aspx?searchtype=IMAGES&artist=22209 Wolf Kahn Artwork Examples on AskART.]\n* [http://www.brooklynrail.org/2007/05/art/wolf-kahn-with-david-kapp-and Wolf Kahn in Conversation with David Kapp and Robert Berlind], Brooklyn Rail, May 2007 \n* [http://www.brooklynrail.org/2011/07/art/wolf-kahn-in-latter-day-focus-color-consequence Wolf Kahn in Latter-Day Focus, Color & Consequence], Brooklyn Rail, July 2011 \n* Documentary film, (2004) [http://www.marlboroproductions.com/movies/wolfkahn.html Wolf Kahn at Niagara Falls]\n* [http://www.newarttv.com/Wolf+Kahn NewArtTV Interview] Part I (2008)\n* [http://newarttv.com/Wolf+Kahn+Part+2+of+2 NewArtTV Interview] Part 2 (2008)\n* [http://nhpr.org/post/inspired-lives-artist-wolf-kahn NHPR Inspired Lives], Interview by Mary Kuechenmeister, 2012\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kahn, Wolf}}\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:American Figurative Expressionism]]\n[[Category:Landscape artists]]\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Art Students League of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brattleboro, Vermont]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American printmakers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:The High School of Music & Art alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German-born American painter|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name         = Wolf Kahn\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Hans Wolfgang Kahn\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1927|10|4}} \n| birth_place  = [[Stuttgart, Germany]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|3|15|1927|10|4}}\n| death_place  = \n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Painting]] and [[Pastels]]\n| training      = [[Hans Hofmann]] <br> [[University of Chicago]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n|website = {{url|wolfkahn.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Wolf Kahn''' (October 4, 1927 \u2013 March 15, 2020)<ref name=\"Death\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.reformer.com/stories/southern-vermont-artist-wolf-kahn-dies-at-age-92,600135 |title=Southern Vermont artist Wolf Kahn dies at age 92 |last=LeConey |first=Bill |last2=Reformer |first2=Brattleboro |date=March 16, 2020 |website=The Brattleboro Reformer |language=en |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]]-born [[United States|American]] [[Painting|painter]].\n\nKahn, known for his combination of [[Realism (arts)|Realism]] and [[Color Field]], worked in [[pastel]] and [[oil paint]]. He studied under [[Hans Hofmann]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and also graduated from the [[University of Chicago]].{{cn|date=March 2018}} Kahn was a resident of both New York City and, during the summer and autumn, [[West Brattleboro, Vermont]].\n\n==Life and career==\nWolf Kahn was born in 1927 in [[Stuttgart, Germany]], the fourth child of Emil and Nellie Budge Kahn. Kahn's father was a notable figure in the music world. He was a musician, composer, conductor, and teacher. Kahn's family was [[Jewish]].<ref>http://www.wolfkahn.com/writing/unlocking-the-unconscious</ref> In 1933, Kahn's father lost his appointment with the Stuttgart Philharmonic Orchestra when [[Adolf Hitler]] came into power and, with increasing [[antisemitism]] sweeping Germany, he and his second wife left Germany with Kahn's three siblings for the United States. Wolf was sent to live with his grandmother, Anna Kahn, in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt, Germany]], at the age of three. He stated that he began drawing at the age of four.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.percontra.net/archive/14kahn.htm|title=Wolf Kahn, The Per Contra Interview with Miriam N. Kotzin|website=www.percontra.net|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n\nIn 1937, the summer of his 11th birthday, his grandmother signed him up for private art lessons with Miss von Joeden. He drew every day and was inspired by military pageantry, [[Napoleonic Wars]] and prominent historical figures including [[Adolph Menzel]] and [[Frederick the Great]]. In 1939, when Kahn was 12 years old, his grandmother arranged for him to leave Germany for England to live with a host family, first with the John Wade family and then with the Purvis Family. As quotas for immigrant applications in the United States changed, Kahn was able to reunite with his family in [[New York City]] in 1940 at the age of 13. {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 1942, Kahn was accepted for his sophomore year at the [[The High School of Music and Art|High School of Music and Art]] in [[New York City]].  His drawings morphed into caricatures.  Kahn cited David Low and Thomas Nast as his favorite cartoonists.<ref>Interview with Wolf Kahn and Justin Spring, July 1995</ref>  His first job was graphics editor of the school newspaper, ''The Overtone''. He graduated in 1945. After a year in the [[U.S. Navy]] after high school, Kahn first attended the [[New School]] to study painting under [[Stuart Davis (painter)|Stuart Davis]].  With the aid of the [[GI Bill]], he was able to continue his studies with [[Abstract Expressionist]] [[Hans Hofmann]] at the Hans Hofmann School.<ref name=\":1\" />  He became Hofmann\u2019s studio assistant by the summer of 1947 at Hofmann's [[Provincetown]], [[Massachusetts]] studio. In 1949, Kahn was accepted into the [[University of Chicago]]'s Hutchins Program, where he completed a bachelor's degree in eight months. {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn 1956, he met fellow painter [[Emily Mason]], who he later joined in [[Venice]], Italy. They married there in March 1957 at the municipal building near the [[Rialto Bridge]], witnessed by strangers and friends including filmmaker [[Tinto Brass]]. In 1958 the couple returned to New York City where Mason gave birth to their first daughter Cecily in 1959. In 1963 the family returned to Italy. Their daughter Melany was born in [[Rome]] in 1964. In 1968 the couple bought a farm in [[Brattleboro, Vermont]] where they continued to summer. Kahn died on March 15, 2020 at the age of 92.<ref name=\"Death\" />\n\n==Wolf Kahn's art==\nKahn worked in oil and pastel.  His works usually cover the subject of [[Landscape art|landscapes]] and his own personal vision of nature.  His convergence of light and color has been described as combining \"pictorial landscapes and painterly abstraction\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/hanshofmann/wolf_kahn_001.html|title=Hans Hofmann . Hofmann\u2019s Legacy . Wolf Kahn \u2013 PBS|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref>\n\n===Influences===\nSurrounded from birth by the work of such artists as [[Hans Thoma]], [[Carl Spitzweg]], [[Wilhelm Trubner]], [[Franz Winterhalter]], by [[Edwardian]]  furniture, books and bronzes of [[Schiller]] and [[Goethe]], it is no wonder that Kahn started drawing at a very young age.  While at the University of Chicago, he became interested in philosophy, particularly the writings of [[Immanuel Kant]] while making sketches of sailboats riding anchor on [[Lake Michigan]].\n\nKahn loved the visual effects of [[Maine]]'s coastline. In the late 1960s after a number of vacations on [[Deer Isle]], Maine, the foggy conditions ultimately led to a significant shift in Kahn's painting.  Years of monochromatic work concentrated on varying tonalities finally gave way to intense color. Kahn recalled later, \"I began to let the color come through on my canvases...my pastels were always intense, and finally my painting caught up with them.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spring|first1=Justin|title=Wolf Kahn|date=2011|publisher=Abrams|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-9790-5|pages=59|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n===Exhibitions===\nKahn's very first exhibition was a group show titled, ''New Provincetown '47'', curated by [[Clement Greenberg]] at the Seligmann Gallery on 57th Street in New York.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spring|first1=|title=Wolf Kahn|date=2011|publisher=|location=|isbn=|pages=21|edition=}}</ref>  The next exhibition would be self-organized by Kahn titled ''813 Broadway'' in 1951.  This was followed by a group exhibition in the fall of 1952 at the Hansa Gallery Cooperative, one of a few Hofmann student spinoffs.  His first one-man solo exhibition would follow in 1953, also at Hansa Gallery, after a summer trip to [[Louisiana]] where he visited his art professor brother, Peter.  A real break came after living and painting in [[Tepoztlan]], Mexico, in a studio space afforded by Mrs. Norman.  Kahn returned to New York City with an offer to join Grace Borgenicht Gallery in 1955.  Her gallery had been in existence on 57th Street since May 1951.  In 1960, Kahn accepted a position as a visiting professor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].  Around this same time, his work was included in a major exhibition at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] titled ''Young America 1960: 30 Painters under 36''. Until his death, Kahn remained very active, still creating new work and exhibiting multiple times per year. <ref>[https://www.artsy.net/artist/wolf-kahn/shows List of past and current exhibitions on Artsy.net]</ref> In Winter of 2017, Kahn celebrated his 90th birthday with an exhibition of over fifty recent paintings at Miles McEnery Gallery (formerly Ameringer | McEnery | Yohe). <ref>[https://hamptonsarthub.com/2017/11/14/exhibitions-nyc-gallery-scene-highlights-through-november-19-2017/ Review of Exhibition ''Hamptons Art Hub'' November 14, 2017]</ref> <ref>[https://www.newcriterion.com/blogs/dispatch/the-critics-notebook-9193 Review of Exhibition, ''Criterion's Critic Notebook'' December 18, 2017]</ref> <ref>[http://www.artnews.com/2018/01/26/new-yorks-ameringer-mcenery-yohe-gallery-renames-expands/ ''New York's Ameringer McEnery Yohe Gallery Renames Itself, Expands'' by Alex Greenberger, Artnews.com, January 26, 2018]</ref> He was represented by several galleries, including [[Addison/Ripley Fine Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://addisonripleyfineart.com/artist/wolf-kahn-pastel/|title=.wolf kahn \u2013 pastel|website=Addison Ripley|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and memberships===\nKahn received a number of awards including a [[Fulbright Scholarship]] in 1962, a John Simon [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] in 1966, and an Award in Art from the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] in 1979.<ref>{{Cite journal | title= Portrait of the Artist's Market | author= Annette Grant | publisher=ARTINFO \u00a0| date= February 9, 2008 | url= http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/26657/portrait-of-the-artists-market/ | accessdate=2008-04-23 | postscript= <!--None--> }}</ref> Kahn received Lifetime Achievement Awards from the Vermont Council on the Arts 1998 and the National Academy in 2006.  He received the University of Chicago Outstanding Alumni Professional Achievement Award in 2012 and the [[United States Department of State|U.S. State Department]] awarded him the International Medal of Art in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/international-medal-of-arts-winner-turns-90-wolf-kahn-shows-his-true-colors,511100|title=International Medal of Arts winner turns 90: Wolf Kahn shows his true colors|last=O'Connor|first=Kevin|date=2017-06-20|work=The Berkshire Eagle|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en}}</ref>  He has honorary doctorates from [[Wheaton College (Massachusetts)|Wheaton College]], 2000<ref>[http://wheatoncollege.edu/college-history/2000s/wolf-kahn/ \"Wolf Kahn, Honorary Degree Recipient\"], Wheaton College History.</ref> and [[Union College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://muse.union.edu/newsarchives/2004/07/page/5/|title=Archives {{!}} Union College News Archives|website=muse.union.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\nKahn became a member of the [[National Academy of Design]] in 1980 and the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] in 1984. He was on the Board of Trustees for [[Marlboro College]], in Marlboro, Vermont, and was an honorary trustee at the Brattleboro Museum in Brattleboro, Vermont.\n\nIn 2005 the Smithsonian Art Collectors Program commissioned Kahn to produce a print to benefit the cultural and educational programs of the [[Smithsonian Associates]].  The screenprint, entitled ''Aura'', hangs in the Graphic Eloquence exhibit in the [[S. Dillon Ripley Center]] on the [[National Mall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artslant.com/ew/artists/show/19487-wolf-kahn|title=Wolf Kahn|website=ArtSlant|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Museum collections===\nKahn's work can be found in numerous museum collections including:\n* [[Art Institute of Chicago]], Chicago, IL<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/73345?search_no=1&index=0|title=Barn in Blue Haze {{!}} The Art Institute of Chicago|website=www.artic.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Boca Raton Museum of Art]], Boca Raton, FL\n* [[Brooklyn Museum]], Brooklyn, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brooklynmuseum.org/opencollection/search?keyword=wolf+kahn|title=Brooklyn Museum|website=www.brooklynmuseum.org|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hirshhorn.si.edu/search-results/search-result-details/?edan_search_value=hmsg_87.5|title=Search Result Details \u2013 Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden {{!}} Smithsonian|work=Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden {{!}} Smithsonian|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* Colby College Museum of Art<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.colby.edu/museum/?s=wolf%20kahn&obj=CUS.18.zoomosd.6054?sid=801&x=9487&x=9488|title=wolf kahn {{!}} Search Results  {{!}} Colby College Museum of Art|work=Colby College Museum of Art|access-date=2018-03-30|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], Los Angeles, CA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.lacma.org/node/248818|title=In Providence, R.I. {{!}} LACMA Collections|website=collections.lacma.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Memorial Art Gallery]], University of Rochester, Rochester, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://magart.rochester.edu/4DACTION/HANDLECGI/CTN1?theKW=Wolf+Kahn&RefineSearch=NewSelection|title=Memorial Art Gallery Collection-Bright Winter Day, 85.61|website=magart.rochester.edu|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search#!?q=wolf%20kahn&perPage=20&sortBy=Relevance&sortOrder=asc&offset=0&pageSize=0|title=Collection|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], Boston, MA<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mfa.org/collections/search|title=Collections Search|website=Museum of Fine Arts, Boston|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy Museum]], New York, NY \n* [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]], Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanart.si.edu/artist/wolf-kahn-2528|title=Wolf Kahn|website=Smithsonian American Art Museum|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* [[National Gallery of Art]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nga.gov/global-site-search-page.html?searchterm=wolf%2520kahn&searchpath=%252Fcontent%252Fngaweb%252FCollection&pageNumber=1|title=Global Site Search Page|website=www.nga.gov|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* Whitney Museum of American Art, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whitney.org/Collection/AllArtists?name=K|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410063840/http://whitney.org/Collection/AllArtists?name=K|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-04-10|title=All Artists {{!}} Whitney Museum of American Art|date=2016-04-10|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref> \n* [[Yale University Art Gallery]], New Haven, CT<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artgallery.yale.edu/collection/search/wolf%20kahn|title=Overview and Highlights|website=artgallery.yale.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n* Ackland Art Museum, University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, NC\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* Marika Herskovic, [http://www.worldcatlibraries.org/oclc/50666793&tab=holdings ''New York School Abstract Expressionists Artists Choice by Artists''] (New York School Press, 2000). {{ISBN|0-9677994-0-6}}, pp.&nbsp;32; 37; 194\u2013197\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.artcyclopedia.com/artists/kahn_wolf.html Wolf Kahn on ARTCYCLOPEDIA]\n* [http://www.askart.com/AskART/artists/search/Search_Repeat.aspx?se